";}i:1;a:10:{s:5:"title";s:35:"Cost of Living and Higher Education";s:4:"link";s:127:"http://www.spatiallink.org/gistools/discuss/weblogs/blogs/pi.php?title=cost_of_living_and_higher_education&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sun, 22 Apr 2007 16:55:57 +0000";s:8:"category";s:7:"spatial";s:4:"guid";s:60:"99@http://www.spatiallink.org/gistools/discuss/weblogs/blogs";s:11:"description";s:1486:"As I returned from the American Planning Association's 2007 National Planning Conference in Philadelphia, I rummaged through some past papers and chanced upon an offer letter that I have been unable to let go of.

When I looked back to why I chose UVA over UPenn, the cost of living at Charlottesville v. Philadelphia, not Public Ivy v. Ivy League, proved to be the determining factor. Although UVA did not play to my strengths in physical design, focusing more on the sociological aspects of planning that I now believe to be closer to the core principles of planning, it was extremely enriching and rewarding.



Thomas Jefferson or William Penn?

So, as some of you may be deciding on which offer letter to accept this fall, here is a little advice mixed with a lot of hope- pick the one you really want and everything else will fall in place. But even if you do not or can not, hard work can even things out.

Good luck!

--?

