--?";s:12:"atom_content";s:1370:"	<p>Here are four "events" from 2006 that I consider as evolutionary milestones of our <a href="http://www.gisuser.com/content/view/9446/">burgeoning</a> <a href="http://www.spatiallink.org/gistools/discuss/weblogs/blogs/pi.php?title=a_rose_by_any_other_name">SIS</a> industry:</p>
	<p>&#8226; <a href="http://www.esri.com/software/arcgis/explorer/">E2</a>- ESRI finally <a href="http://www.spatiallink.org/gistools/discuss/weblogs/blogs/pi.php?title=esri_ketchup">catches up</a> to GE. Almost<br />
&#8226; <a href="http://maps.live.com/">Virtual Earth</a>- Microsoft adds the ability to add and save shapes, and browser-based GE-esque 3D views<br />
&#8226; <a href="http://earth.google.com/">GE</a>- Google gulps <a href="">SketchUp</a> and consolidates GE's usergroups by jumping head-first in <a href="http://www.spatiallink.org/gistools/discuss/weblogs/blogs/pi.php?title=follow_up_1_esri_ketchup">collaborations</a><br />
&#8226; Spatial Web Services- Be it ESRI's <a href="http://arcwebservices.com/">ArcWeb Services</a> with <a href="http://www.globexplorer.com/">GlobeXplorer</a>, or <a href="http://www.dmsolutions.ca/">DM Solutions Group</a>'s <a href="http://www.mapsherpa.com/">MapSherpa Spatial Web Services</a> and <a href="http://www.mapgears.com/">Mapgears</a>, spatial web services gain a firmer footing at the enterprise level.</p>
	<p>--&#960;
